WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.280 --> 00:00:03.000
So welcome those of you who are here.

2
00:00:03.060 --> 00:00:04.540
Thanks for coming to our session.

3
00:00:05.760 --> 00:00:09.570
We're going to spend the next hour and a half or so thinking about

4
00:00:10.680 --> 00:00:14.540
generally lifestyle choices in terms of cancer development,

5
00:00:14.660 --> 00:00:18.160
cancer therapy. I'm going to cover diet,

6
00:00:18.520 --> 00:00:22.480
some aspects of diet, exercise, and the

7
00:00:22.500 --> 00:00:25.920
influence of the microbiome. So I'm Karen Valston.

8
00:00:26.040 --> 00:00:28.920
I'm going to give the first talk about precision diets,

9
00:00:29.860 --> 00:00:31.820
and then we have two other speakers, as you see.

10
00:00:32.820 --> 00:00:36.020
So, okay, my slides are up. That's fantastic.

11
00:00:37.600 --> 00:00:40.640
Well, clearly, there's a lot of interest in diet.

12
00:00:40.890 --> 00:00:42.760
Diet and health, diet and disease,

13
00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:45.020
a huge industry.

14
00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:49.900
But I think it's probably fair to say that we still have a lot to

15
00:00:49.980 --> 00:00:53.260
learn about how diet influences cancer

16
00:00:53.280 --> 00:00:57.180
development and the aspect that we're particularly interested in, how

17
00:00:57.190 --> 00:01:00.160
diet can either help to augment

18
00:01:01.040 --> 00:01:02.060
cancer treatment.

19
00:01:03.080 --> 00:01:06.900
So obviously, diet provides all the nutrients

20
00:01:07.080 --> 00:01:09.940
for metabolism in both normal and cancer cells.

21
00:01:09.950 --> 00:01:13.810
So diet is important for all of our tissues, healthy and

22
00:01:13.840 --> 00:01:17.360
diseased. And we know,

23
00:01:17.420 --> 00:01:20.740
obviously, that changes in diet can change the

24
00:01:20.780 --> 00:01:24.240
availability of nutrients and can have

25
00:01:24.620 --> 00:01:26.640
particularly profound effects on our health.

26
00:01:26.740 --> 00:01:30.700
If we think of vitamin deficiencies or mineral deficiencies, it's very

27
00:01:30.780 --> 00:01:33.840
obvious that diet is important for maintaining normal health.

28
00:01:34.800 --> 00:01:35.020
So

29
00:01:36.140 --> 00:01:39.580
many years ago now, while Oliver was in the lab with me, he

30
00:01:39.740 --> 00:01:43.500
decided that he would like to see whether there were any selective

31
00:01:43.660 --> 00:01:47.200
nutritional requirements of cancer cells that we might be able to

32
00:01:47.260 --> 00:01:51.190
harness therapeutically. And he started doing these experiments in

33
00:01:51.220 --> 00:01:54.860
tissue culture systems, looking at the requirements for

34
00:01:54.940 --> 00:01:58.340
nonessential amino acids in a variety of cancer cells.

35
00:01:58.400 --> 00:02:02.160
So he used nonessential amino acids because he didn't necessarily want

36
00:02:02.260 --> 00:02:06.040
to affect normal tissue. And what he

37
00:02:06.140 --> 00:02:10.100
found was that many cancer cells are very

38
00:02:10.140 --> 00:02:13.800
dependent on an exogenous supply of the two

39
00:02:13.820 --> 00:02:17.299
nonessential amino acids, serine and glycine.

40
00:02:17.380 --> 00:02:20.600
Now they are nonessential, which means, of course, that most of

41
00:02:20.680 --> 00:02:21.580
our

42
00:02:23.060 --> 00:02:26.660
cells can make serine and glycine de novo from glucose.

43
00:02:27.200 --> 00:02:30.880
So the first question, of course, is, is it really feasible to modulate

44
00:02:30.920 --> 00:02:34.820
serine and glycine through diet, given that our entire bodies can make serine and

45
00:02:34.860 --> 00:02:38.800
glycine? And we discovered, and many others have confirmed this, that indeed,

46
00:02:38.840 --> 00:02:42.620
if you feed mice on a serine glycine limited diet, you

47
00:02:42.720 --> 00:02:46.180
can reduce the amount of circulating serine and glycine.

48
00:02:46.580 --> 00:02:49.940
And in fact, we have done some trials in normal healthy

49
00:02:50.020 --> 00:02:53.820
volunteers and found that you can also reduce circulating levels of

50
00:02:53.900 --> 00:02:57.740
serine and glycine in people by feeding them on a serine glycine

51
00:02:57.780 --> 00:02:58.820
restricted diet.

52
00:03:00.260 --> 00:03:04.020
So serine and glycine, the reason we use both is because they're very

53
00:03:04.120 --> 00:03:07.780
easily interconvertible through loss or gain of a one carbon unit,

54
00:03:08.340 --> 00:03:11.560
and they're important for many processes.

55
00:03:11.600 --> 00:03:12.640
They're important for

56
00:03:17.100 --> 00:03:20.420
feeding the folate cycle, the one carbon cycle, and the production of

57
00:03:20.460 --> 00:03:24.260
nucleotides. Important in contributing to the

58
00:03:24.280 --> 00:03:27.740
methionine cycle and the methylation of DNA, RNA,

59
00:03:27.900 --> 00:03:31.420
proteins, lipids, all those important processes.

60
00:03:32.920 --> 00:03:36.760
But what we've become particularly interested in is this role of

61
00:03:36.860 --> 00:03:40.100
serine and glycine in supporting

62
00:03:40.160 --> 00:03:43.720
antioxidant defense through both the production of

63
00:03:43.800 --> 00:03:47.520
NADPH, and providing

64
00:03:47.560 --> 00:03:48.840
reducing equivalents for

65
00:03:49.900 --> 00:03:53.700
antioxidative reactions and the production of

66
00:03:53.740 --> 00:03:57.570
glutathione. Of course, one of the principal antioxidants that we have

67
00:03:58.060 --> 00:04:00.740
protecting ourselves from oxidative stress.

68
00:04:01.920 --> 00:04:05.860
So moving on over the next years, Oliver and then later

69
00:04:06.180 --> 00:04:09.500
Vasilis, who's now in my lab, have shown that in many

70
00:04:09.920 --> 00:04:13.800
actual tumor models in mice, you can recapitulate

71
00:04:13.810 --> 00:04:17.760
those in vitro experiments by showing that feeding mice on a serine

72
00:04:17.820 --> 00:04:21.810
glycine free diet can lead to slower

73
00:04:21.921 --> 00:04:25.640
tumor growth, longer survival, and less metastasis in a

74
00:04:25.680 --> 00:04:28.840
number of different genetically engineered models or

75
00:04:28.960 --> 00:04:32.640
orthotopic types of models. So it

76
00:04:32.650 --> 00:04:36.580
seems that at least in these model systems, limiting

77
00:04:36.620 --> 00:04:40.100
serine and glycine through diet can have a therapeutic benefit

78
00:04:41.200 --> 00:04:41.800
just alone.

79
00:04:43.100 --> 00:04:47.020
But obviously we limit tumor growth, but we don't cure the

80
00:04:47.040 --> 00:04:51.020
mice. And so the question then becomes, can we combine the

81
00:04:51.040 --> 00:04:53.400
serine glycine free diet with something else?

82
00:04:53.920 --> 00:04:57.680
Now, as I mentioned a moment ago, serine and glycine are important for

83
00:04:57.760 --> 00:04:59.520
protection from oxidative stress.

84
00:04:59.560 --> 00:05:03.500
And we can see again in tissue culture cells that if we grow

85
00:05:03.540 --> 00:05:07.260
the cells in the absence of serine, they become much more sensitive to

86
00:05:07.320 --> 00:05:09.969
oxidative stress. In this case, we're just giving the cells

87
00:05:10.680 --> 00:05:14.170
peroxide. And so the question then we asked was,

88
00:05:14.660 --> 00:05:18.560
is it possible that serine glycine depletion would cooperate with

89
00:05:18.620 --> 00:05:22.540
chemo or radiotherapy, both of which we know function to

90
00:05:22.560 --> 00:05:26.230
a large part by inducing ROS, inducing oxidative

91
00:05:26.300 --> 00:05:28.400
stress and thereby killing cancer cells.

92
00:05:28.460 --> 00:05:32.300
So would this combination work? And in fact, my lab

93
00:05:32.320 --> 00:05:36.220
didn't do the experiment. Oliver when he went on to start his own lab and did this

94
00:05:36.320 --> 00:05:39.900
nice experiment where he showed that in a tumor model

95
00:05:41.360 --> 00:05:45.260
he could treat the mice with a serine glycine free diet or he could treat

96
00:05:45.280 --> 00:05:49.180
the tumors using radiotherapy. And you can see that there's some

97
00:05:49.220 --> 00:05:51.720
response in terms of the cell death.

98
00:05:52.220 --> 00:05:55.840
But clearly when he uses both a serine glycine free diet and

99
00:05:55.920 --> 00:05:59.580
radiotherapy, that response is greatly enhanced.

100
00:05:59.620 --> 00:06:03.540
So there's a lot more death. So there's some, I think, merit

101
00:06:03.600 --> 00:06:07.360
to the suggestion that there may be a good combination of increasing

102
00:06:07.420 --> 00:06:10.380
ROS and using a serine glycine free

103
00:06:10.480 --> 00:06:13.836
diet.And interestingly, Thalas

104
00:06:14.156 --> 00:06:16.426
Papaji has shown really nicely that

105
00:06:17.296 --> 00:06:21.156
when tumors try to activate their antioxidative

106
00:06:21.296 --> 00:06:24.596
pathways, that in itself produces a

107
00:06:24.616 --> 00:06:27.236
requirement for serine and glycine.

108
00:06:27.276 --> 00:06:30.696
And so there's a kind of maybe a virtuous circle here where increased

109
00:06:30.736 --> 00:06:34.676
ROS drives an even further response to the

110
00:06:34.696 --> 00:06:36.336
serine/glycine-free diet.

111
00:06:37.916 --> 00:06:39.636
So I've told you all the good part here.

112
00:06:39.716 --> 00:06:43.416
We do see this effect in many cancer cells, but not all.

113
00:06:43.486 --> 00:06:47.256
And it's very clear that not all tumors respond to this serine/glycine

114
00:06:47.316 --> 00:06:51.016
depletion approach. And this is just illustrated here by two

115
00:06:51.116 --> 00:06:53.636
genetically engineered models of lung cancer.

116
00:06:54.176 --> 00:06:58.116
Here we're looking at the RAS LKB1-driven lung cancers, and you can see

117
00:06:58.176 --> 00:07:02.146
very nicely the survival benefit of putting these mice onto

118
00:07:02.176 --> 00:07:05.996
a serine/glycine-free diet. But if we take more or

119
00:07:06.036 --> 00:07:09.196
less the same tumor model, but we substitute deletion of

120
00:07:09.256 --> 00:07:13.016
p53 for LKB, here in this RAS p53

121
00:07:13.076 --> 00:07:17.016
lung cancer model, there's absolutely no impact of the serine/glycine-free

122
00:07:17.096 --> 00:07:20.536
diet. And we see the same in the RAS p53-driven

123
00:07:20.656 --> 00:07:24.316
pancreas cancers. So why do not all

124
00:07:24.396 --> 00:07:28.236
cancers respond? Well, another way of asking that

125
00:07:28.276 --> 00:07:32.096
is how do these cancer cells become independent of exogenous serine and

126
00:07:32.136 --> 00:07:35.956
glycine? And one obvious way, which I've already alluded to, is that cells can make

127
00:07:35.996 --> 00:07:39.696
their own serine and glycine. So we can, in many

128
00:07:39.816 --> 00:07:43.376
tumors, we see an increase in the pathway here, the de novo

129
00:07:43.476 --> 00:07:47.386
pathway of serine synthesis, particularly increase in expression of

130
00:07:47.416 --> 00:07:50.596
this first rate-limiting step driven by the enzyme

131
00:07:50.676 --> 00:07:54.636
PHGDH. So we see often that many tumor

132
00:07:54.716 --> 00:07:58.316
cells increase the expression of the de novo serine

133
00:07:58.356 --> 00:08:02.136
synthesis pathway and become less dependent on exogenous

134
00:08:02.146 --> 00:08:05.956
serine. And you can see that here, for example, in a breast cancer

135
00:08:06.456 --> 00:08:10.236
cell line that has an amplified, serine synthesis pathway.

136
00:08:10.716 --> 00:08:14.456
If we take serine and glycine away from these cells, they really don't care.

137
00:08:14.496 --> 00:08:15.636
They're completely indifferent.

138
00:08:16.516 --> 00:08:19.256
They're relying very heavily on this de novo

139
00:08:19.316 --> 00:08:22.836
pathway. This was first described by Rich

140
00:08:22.876 --> 00:08:24.056
Crobimato and

141
00:08:25.356 --> 00:08:29.296
David Sabatini and Matt Vander Heiden many years ago when we first started in

142
00:08:29.356 --> 00:08:30.216
these experiments.

143
00:08:31.296 --> 00:08:31.516
So,

144
00:08:32.317 --> 00:08:36.196
if you go back now and just look in cBioPortal, you see that in fact, many

145
00:08:36.437 --> 00:08:40.317
tumors, many different types of tumors, at least a proportion of the tumors show

146
00:08:40.396 --> 00:08:43.256
evidence of amplification of this serine synthesis pathway.

147
00:08:43.696 --> 00:08:47.536
So it does seem to be a common event for tumor cells to

148
00:08:47.596 --> 00:08:51.116
ramp up their own ability to make serine and glycine.

149
00:08:51.196 --> 00:08:54.236
And so in these cases, obviously, serine

150
00:08:54.296 --> 00:08:56.596
starvation doesn't have any effect.

151
00:08:56.956 --> 00:09:00.656
And the answer there clearly would be, let's use an inhibitor

152
00:09:00.776 --> 00:09:02.616
of this serine synthesis pathway.

153
00:09:02.686 --> 00:09:06.336
So an inhibitor of this PHGDH enzyme, these inhibitors

154
00:09:06.396 --> 00:09:10.336
are available. So Milene, while she was in the lab, thought she'd

155
00:09:10.516 --> 00:09:14.016
try this approach. So she used a cell line that was

156
00:09:14.036 --> 00:09:17.196
resistant to exogenous serine depletion.

157
00:09:17.256 --> 00:09:21.056
We're looking at here are organoids grown from these tumors.

158
00:09:21.116 --> 00:09:23.976
These are now APC RAS-driven colon tumors.

159
00:09:24.836 --> 00:09:27.196
Putting on the inhibitor really doesn't stop their growth.

160
00:09:27.536 --> 00:09:29.796
Taking away serine and glycine has no effect.

161
00:09:29.856 --> 00:09:33.516
But together, you can see you can very profoundly inhibit the growth of these

162
00:09:33.556 --> 00:09:37.436
tumor cells and also the tumors

163
00:09:37.856 --> 00:09:40.536
in mice by using this combination diet.

164
00:09:43.196 --> 00:09:47.156
Julia, since then, has been trying to expand on this and think about are there

165
00:09:47.256 --> 00:09:49.316
other ways in which we can find

166
00:09:50.896 --> 00:09:54.156
genes that may be particularly important in these

167
00:09:54.336 --> 00:09:56.636
serine/glycine-resistant cell lines.

168
00:09:57.676 --> 00:10:01.396
And she just did a CRISPR dropout screen in one of these particular cell

169
00:10:01.416 --> 00:10:01.836
lines,

170
00:10:02.756 --> 00:10:05.736
and looked to see which genes became

171
00:10:06.396 --> 00:10:10.176
conditionally important under conditions of serine/glycine

172
00:10:10.236 --> 00:10:13.756
depletion. So we think the screen worked because we got all

173
00:10:13.916 --> 00:10:17.456
three components of the serine synthesis pathway, which of course you would

174
00:10:17.496 --> 00:10:21.276
expect. We also picked up numerous mitochondrial

175
00:10:21.336 --> 00:10:24.916
transporters. They were significantly enriched, a whole list of them,

176
00:10:25.916 --> 00:10:29.736
suggesting-- oh, we can just see that, an example of one of them

177
00:10:29.856 --> 00:10:31.675
here. This is the folate transporter.

178
00:10:32.216 --> 00:10:36.126
You can see that under normal conditions, serine/glycine fed conditions,

179
00:10:36.236 --> 00:10:38.676
taking away this folate transporter really doesn't

180
00:10:39.656 --> 00:10:41.416
have any effect on the cell growth.

181
00:10:42.396 --> 00:10:45.796
But if we take away the serine and glycine and knock down

182
00:10:45.816 --> 00:10:49.276
expression of this folate transporter, the cells can't grow at

183
00:10:49.396 --> 00:10:52.916
all. They also can't migrate, which is interesting, I think,

184
00:10:53.056 --> 00:10:56.456
because obviously growth and migration, different things.

185
00:10:56.476 --> 00:10:59.996
And again, the tumors, which themselves are resistant to

186
00:11:00.016 --> 00:11:03.236
serine/glycine depleted diets, become

187
00:11:03.396 --> 00:11:06.656
sensitive once they've lost expression of this folate

188
00:11:06.696 --> 00:11:10.316
transporter. And this really is very

189
00:11:11.076 --> 00:11:15.016
similar to work that was published by Lou Cantley, showing that

190
00:11:15.456 --> 00:11:19.276
sort of an intact mitochondrial folate cycle

191
00:11:19.356 --> 00:11:23.316
was important for cells. Interestingly, these cells actually

192
00:11:23.356 --> 00:11:26.756
become glycine auxotrophs, not serine auxotrophs.

193
00:11:26.876 --> 00:11:30.216
So there is some argument that potentially,

194
00:11:30.996 --> 00:11:34.576
combining glycine starvation and mitochondrial

195
00:11:34.596 --> 00:11:38.286
one-carbon cycle inhibitors may be another interesting therapeutic

196
00:11:38.316 --> 00:11:42.176
approach for these types of tumors, and one that we haven't explored

197
00:11:42.216 --> 00:11:43.326
yet experimentally.

198
00:11:44.856 --> 00:11:48.796
But other than increasing de novo serine synthesis, are there other

199
00:11:48.836 --> 00:11:52.566
ways in which cells can become independent of dietary serine and

200
00:11:52.616 --> 00:11:56.496
glycine? And another obvious candidate here is for

201
00:11:56.576 --> 00:11:59.456
the tumor cells to access serine from their

202
00:11:59.516 --> 00:12:00.716
surrounding

203
00:12:01.816 --> 00:12:05.156
stromal cells, the normal stroma cells in the

204
00:12:05.216 --> 00:12:09.136
tumor. And Alec Kimmelman and Robert Barn had a

205
00:12:09.196 --> 00:12:12.876
lovely paper showing that in fact, neurons can release serine to

206
00:12:12.896 --> 00:12:16.570
support pancreatic cancers.And

207
00:12:16.620 --> 00:12:19.810
Yong-Hwan in my lab has been looking at the potential impact of

208
00:12:19.820 --> 00:12:23.280
adipocytes. So we know that there are very important

209
00:12:23.320 --> 00:12:27.200
adipocyte tumor interactions. And what he found was that, in

210
00:12:27.240 --> 00:12:31.120
fact, if you take adipocytes and you starve them of serine and glycine, they

211
00:12:31.160 --> 00:12:34.800
very efficiently upregulate their own de novo serine synthesis

212
00:12:34.840 --> 00:12:38.690
pathway to the extent that they can provide their own serine and

213
00:12:38.720 --> 00:12:42.620
excrete serine. They make enough serine to excrete it into the medium and

214
00:12:42.640 --> 00:12:46.210
glycine. And therefore, not surprisingly, if we take adipocyte

215
00:12:46.260 --> 00:12:50.059
condition medium and grow-- these are now cells that are sensitive to

216
00:12:50.100 --> 00:12:53.700
exogenous serine and glycine, we can rescue

217
00:12:53.920 --> 00:12:56.700
their growth under serine and glycine starvation.

218
00:12:56.989 --> 00:13:00.420
And that rescue depends on the serine synthesis

219
00:13:00.540 --> 00:13:04.060
pathway activity in the adipocytes, because if we make condition

220
00:13:04.140 --> 00:13:07.800
medium from adipocytes that have been given a PHGDH

221
00:13:07.860 --> 00:13:09.880
inhibitor, this doesn't work.

222
00:13:11.480 --> 00:13:15.140
These are very preliminary experiments, but if we now look at

223
00:13:15.200 --> 00:13:19.100
circulating levels of serine and glycine, we can see that if we

224
00:13:19.140 --> 00:13:23.040
deplete adipocytes of their ability to make serine, so if

225
00:13:23.080 --> 00:13:26.900
we use an adipocyte specific PHGDH knockout and

226
00:13:26.920 --> 00:13:30.880
combine this with a serine glycine free diet, we can see that we can

227
00:13:30.960 --> 00:13:34.430
lower the circulating levels of serine and glycine, suggesting

228
00:13:34.460 --> 00:13:38.180
that circulating serine and glycine, to some degree, comes from

229
00:13:38.220 --> 00:13:41.740
adipocytes. And our question now is, is this actually

230
00:13:41.760 --> 00:13:45.340
important for tumor and supporting tumor, and is this more

231
00:13:45.420 --> 00:13:49.260
evident under conditions of obesity, where simplistically there are more

232
00:13:49.280 --> 00:13:53.120
adipocytes? So is it possible that under conditions of obesity,

233
00:13:53.180 --> 00:13:56.930
there's more availability of serine that's derived from the adipocytes?

234
00:13:58.600 --> 00:14:02.580
So that's all fine and dandy. We can think about many experiments

235
00:14:02.620 --> 00:14:06.020
that we can do using serine depletion or

236
00:14:06.140 --> 00:14:08.820
inhibition of serine synthesis in

237
00:14:09.840 --> 00:14:13.720
tumor therapies. But the obvious question then becomes, does this

238
00:14:13.960 --> 00:14:16.480
actually result in any unwanted toxicities?

239
00:14:16.820 --> 00:14:20.720
We're obviously focused on the effect of these combinations on the

240
00:14:20.780 --> 00:14:24.660
tumor cells, but does it have any effect on the normal cells

241
00:14:24.699 --> 00:14:25.220
in the body?

242
00:14:26.199 --> 00:14:28.080
And going back to Mylene's

243
00:14:29.300 --> 00:14:33.160
work, where she uses combinations of serine depleted

244
00:14:33.240 --> 00:14:36.440
diets and inhibitors of the serine synthesis pathway,

245
00:14:37.500 --> 00:14:41.480
we did notice that that did result in weight

246
00:14:41.520 --> 00:14:44.750
loss in the mice that had to be managed quite carefully by

247
00:14:44.820 --> 00:14:47.240
toggling the amount of the inhibitor.

248
00:14:47.760 --> 00:14:51.060
It was very easily rescued, and it didn't seem to correlate with

249
00:14:51.140 --> 00:14:52.900
any clear

250
00:14:53.900 --> 00:14:57.410
damage of any organs or clear abnormalities in the mice.

251
00:14:57.480 --> 00:14:59.740
The mice recovered from this very quickly.

252
00:14:59.750 --> 00:15:03.680
You can see here that we didn't see any overt damage to the

253
00:15:03.700 --> 00:15:06.140
brain, to the liver, or to the kidney.

254
00:15:06.840 --> 00:15:10.440
As far as we could tell, at least these were short term assays over weeks.

255
00:15:10.760 --> 00:15:14.740
The mice were perfectly fine, and if they did lose weight, they recovered that very

256
00:15:14.800 --> 00:15:18.480
quickly when we took away the inhibitor or fed them again with

257
00:15:18.520 --> 00:15:22.240
serine and glycine. However, to be fair, there have been a few

258
00:15:22.320 --> 00:15:26.040
studies to show that, in fact, serine and glycine depletion does have an

259
00:15:26.120 --> 00:15:30.000
impact on normal physiology. There's this very nice paper from Christian

260
00:15:30.060 --> 00:15:33.660
Metallo showing that long-term serine and glycine

261
00:15:33.680 --> 00:15:36.980
depletion in mice, and now we're talking about months to a year,

262
00:15:37.620 --> 00:15:40.880
can lead to peripheral neuropathy.

263
00:15:41.340 --> 00:15:45.140
So these mice stop feeling so much in their paws.

264
00:15:45.220 --> 00:15:48.260
You can put them on a hot plate, and they don't jump up and down so much.

265
00:15:49.020 --> 00:15:52.720
And there are many studies showing the importance of serine

266
00:15:52.860 --> 00:15:56.580
in T cell responses. We have tried to look at

267
00:15:56.640 --> 00:16:00.380
this, not very extensively, I'll admit, and as far as we could

268
00:16:00.460 --> 00:16:04.080
tell, we were not able to see any changes in T cell

269
00:16:04.180 --> 00:16:07.880
infiltration in the tumors from mice that had been fed on a

270
00:16:07.900 --> 00:16:11.560
serine glycine free diet compared to mice fed on a full

271
00:16:11.620 --> 00:16:15.400
diet. But I think that we have to accept that it is very

272
00:16:15.440 --> 00:16:18.940
likely, and Josh has done some beautiful work here, that

273
00:16:19.060 --> 00:16:23.000
serine and the products of the serine pathway formate and

274
00:16:23.040 --> 00:16:26.520
the whole folate cycle will, to some degree,

275
00:16:26.660 --> 00:16:30.380
impede T cell responses. So I think this is a caveat that we

276
00:16:30.600 --> 00:16:31.739
really need to think about.

277
00:16:33.080 --> 00:16:36.880
However, we've also been looking at the response to

278
00:16:36.900 --> 00:16:39.200
serine and glycine, but in a different context.

279
00:16:39.240 --> 00:16:43.040
So I mentioned that sometimes when we put mice on a serine glycine

280
00:16:43.080 --> 00:16:46.440
free diet, they lose weight, particularly if we combine that with a

281
00:16:46.460 --> 00:16:50.380
PHGDH inhibitor. But even just the mice that are normally on

282
00:16:50.420 --> 00:16:52.860
the diet do lose a little body weight.

283
00:16:52.920 --> 00:16:55.220
You can see that here, I hope, in the orange line.

284
00:16:55.930 --> 00:16:59.580
That happens initially when the mice go on the diet, and that does stabilize, so

285
00:16:59.640 --> 00:17:02.840
the body weight doesn't continue to drop, and the mice

286
00:17:03.700 --> 00:17:05.840
are fine. They're perfectly healthy.

287
00:17:06.161 --> 00:17:09.881
They just always remain slightly lighter, and the reason that they're lighter is

288
00:17:09.921 --> 00:17:11.980
that they have less fat,

289
00:17:13.340 --> 00:17:16.300
both subcutaneous and visceral. And you can see that the

290
00:17:16.340 --> 00:17:20.320
adipocytes in that fat are smaller when the mice are fed on a

291
00:17:20.340 --> 00:17:21.881
serine glycine free diet.

292
00:17:23.421 --> 00:17:26.820
And so our question became, does this reduction in body weight

293
00:17:26.901 --> 00:17:30.200
impact the rate of cachexia? So,

294
00:17:30.900 --> 00:17:34.780
this is a sort of a slightly alternative approach

295
00:17:34.840 --> 00:17:38.670
to thinking about this problem. But, as you all know, of

296
00:17:38.760 --> 00:17:42.260
course, cachexia is that debilitating weight loss,

297
00:17:42.680 --> 00:17:46.320
unwanted weight loss that's seen in many cancer

298
00:17:46.380 --> 00:17:50.320
types and is really a particularly big problem in

299
00:17:50.400 --> 00:17:54.040
that it limits life expectancy, it

300
00:17:54.080 --> 00:17:57.640
limits treatment option, and it's very poorly

301
00:17:57.650 --> 00:18:01.600
understood. And there's a

302
00:18:01.640 --> 00:18:05.460
very nice consortium led by Eileen

303
00:18:05.540 --> 00:18:09.252
White looking into this particular problem.So

304
00:18:09.912 --> 00:18:13.752
our initial expectation, I guess, it was that if you

305
00:18:13.772 --> 00:18:17.732
feed mice on a serine/glycine-free diet and they're lighter, they may be

306
00:18:17.792 --> 00:18:21.552
less able to cope with tumors that induce cachexia.

307
00:18:22.172 --> 00:18:26.102
And you can see here that one of these tumor types, the K-RAS/LKB1

308
00:18:26.112 --> 00:18:26.712
lung model,

309
00:18:27.652 --> 00:18:29.972
we had exactly the opposite response.

310
00:18:30.372 --> 00:18:34.332
In fact, the mice that were on the serine/glycine-free diet showed less weight

311
00:18:34.372 --> 00:18:37.052
loss than the mice that were on the control diet.

312
00:18:38.332 --> 00:18:42.152
Now, the problem with this particular experiment is something that I showed you

313
00:18:42.252 --> 00:18:46.041
earlier, which is in this model, the serine/glycine-free diet actually delays

314
00:18:46.112 --> 00:18:47.092
tumor genesis.

315
00:18:48.102 --> 00:18:51.972
So the question here becomes, is serine/glycine starvation actually doing something

316
00:18:52.012 --> 00:18:55.992
to cachexia, or is it just delaying tumor progression, and so naturally

317
00:18:56.032 --> 00:18:58.052
the cachexic response comes later?

318
00:18:58.892 --> 00:19:02.852
So in order to answer that, we turn to the other model

319
00:19:02.872 --> 00:19:06.672
that I showed you earlier, the K-RAS/p53 cancer model, where we

320
00:19:06.762 --> 00:19:10.352
don't see an impact on tumor progression, tumor growth.

321
00:19:10.992 --> 00:19:14.952
And again, here we see that while the mice on the diet

322
00:19:14.992 --> 00:19:18.892
are slightly lighter, they don't lose weight the way that the mice on the

323
00:19:18.932 --> 00:19:22.292
control diet do. This is looking at visceral WAT,

324
00:19:23.152 --> 00:19:26.792
subcutaneous WAT. And here's an orthotopic pancreatic model.

325
00:19:26.852 --> 00:19:30.092
This is a lung cancer, this is a pancreas cancer, and again, we see

326
00:19:30.472 --> 00:19:34.252
exactly the same thing. Obviously, this is a work in progress.

327
00:19:34.992 --> 00:19:38.392
But initially what we can say is that serine/glycine

328
00:19:38.652 --> 00:19:42.312
starvation somehow limits the induction of the

329
00:19:42.332 --> 00:19:45.972
cachectic and inflammatory markers

330
00:19:46.332 --> 00:19:49.992
that have been associated with this body weight loss

331
00:19:50.112 --> 00:19:53.342
under normal conditions. So here you can see that

332
00:19:53.372 --> 00:19:57.352
GDF15, which is strongly associated with cachexia, is not so

333
00:19:57.362 --> 00:20:00.812
strongly increased in the mice on the serine/glycine-free diet.

334
00:20:01.292 --> 00:20:05.222
Similarly here with plasma IL6, which again has been

335
00:20:05.432 --> 00:20:09.192
related to cachexia. And I know you can't see

336
00:20:09.252 --> 00:20:12.772
this, but basically what we're doing here is we're asking in our two models

337
00:20:13.132 --> 00:20:16.112
what's down compared to mice on normal chow.

338
00:20:16.532 --> 00:20:20.352
And what you see here down at the bottom are many inflammatory markers

339
00:20:20.412 --> 00:20:24.312
that are less highly expressed in the circulation of

340
00:20:24.352 --> 00:20:26.632
mice that are on a serine/glycine-free diet.

341
00:20:27.212 --> 00:20:30.992
So initially at least, the working hypothesis is that serine/glycine

342
00:20:31.032 --> 00:20:34.532
limitation can somehow provoke a healthier systemic

343
00:20:34.592 --> 00:20:38.512
response. There's less inflammation, and somehow that provides

344
00:20:38.572 --> 00:20:42.442
some protection from cachexia. And what we're trying to do now is

345
00:20:42.512 --> 00:20:46.072
answer the question, if we look at people who are very lean,

346
00:20:46.532 --> 00:20:50.332
below normal BMI, do they also show this

347
00:20:50.432 --> 00:20:53.892
delay or somehow protection from cachexia that may be

348
00:20:53.952 --> 00:20:57.592
unrelated to the actual progression of their tumor?

349
00:20:59.052 --> 00:21:02.812
Oops, going backwards. Okay, so just a final word

350
00:21:02.892 --> 00:21:06.012
then. I think we, at least in the lab, are convinced that

351
00:21:06.792 --> 00:21:10.112
we should be pursuing something that is called precision

352
00:21:10.172 --> 00:21:13.812
nutrition. And just like every other precision

353
00:21:13.872 --> 00:21:14.352
medicine,

354
00:21:15.292 --> 00:21:19.052
that depends on a much better mechanistic understanding

355
00:21:19.472 --> 00:21:23.432
of what the nutritional vulnerabilities of different cancers might be.

356
00:21:23.952 --> 00:21:27.672
And can we really harness that mechanistic understanding to

357
00:21:27.712 --> 00:21:30.872
devise clever new ways to treat these tumors?

358
00:21:31.892 --> 00:21:35.352
And that's all that's left to me then is to thank my lab.

359
00:21:35.492 --> 00:21:39.252
I've mentioned the people who did the work, people who are still in the lab, people

360
00:21:39.292 --> 00:21:42.392
who have left the lab and gone on to bigger and better things, and all of our

361
00:21:42.432 --> 00:21:46.112
wonderful collaborators. And I think I have a few

362
00:21:46.172 --> 00:21:49.992
minutes left in case there are any questions. So thank you for listening.

363
00:21:55.232 --> 00:21:55.612
Mark.

364
00:21:56.232 --> 00:22:00.101
That was very nice. I'm not sure if this

365
00:22:00.101 --> 00:22:03.032
is on. I think so.

